    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so i'm buying a house in austin and things are moving fast. my agent said i need to put my earnest money into an escrow account, but i dont really get why i cant just hold onto it or pay the seller directly until the deal is done. why does a third party need to hold it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A third party holding your earnest money, or \"earnest money,\" is a necessary measure to keep things orderly. It's like a good-faith deposit, and holding it in escrow prevents a messy situation where one party might suddenly decide to pull the plug or try to cheat the other side. If you just handed it over to the seller, and then the deal fell apart, you'd be left with a big, messy argument, and that's not how a proper transaction works. The escrow agent is the neutral ground, making sure everyone plays by the rules.",
